gl9 — OpenGL for 9front. Changelog.
(`pac9 changelog gl9` shows this; newest first.)

0.2.1 — 2026-07-17
  Rebuilt against a correctness pass on the cc9 C runtime (durable fsync, honest
  file locks, correct O_APPEND, per-thread errno, corrected float formatting).
  gl9 itself is unchanged — same OpenGL 3.3, same softpipe/llvmpipe dual build,
  same runtime rasterizer pick — and both demos re-render pixel content on bare
  metal. This is a substrate-only refresh so gl9 rides the same honest runtime
  as the rest of the ports.

0.2.0 — 2026-07-15
  llvmpipe: ~15x faster OpenGL, when your kernel allows it.

  gl9 now ships Mesa's llvmpipe alongside softpipe and picks between them
  automatically. llvmpipe JIT-compiles shaders to x86-64 at runtime; softpipe
  is the scalar reference rasterizer. They render identically, pixel for pixel
  — this is purely a speed choice.

  Measured on bare metal (Shuttle DS57U, Broadwell), 512x512 per-pixel Phong:

      softpipe   220-269 ms/frame    3.7-4.5 fps
      llvmpipe   14.7-16.5 ms/frame  60-68 fps      (15.0x and 16.2x)

  llvmpipe's FIRST frame costs ~820 ms more (it compiles the shaders once), so
  it breaks even after ~4 frames. Great for anything sustained; a real cost for
  a one-shot render.

  REQUIRES A PATCHED KERNEL for the fast path. llvmpipe writes machine code at
  runtime and jumps to it, which needs writable+executable memory. Stock 9front
  NX-enforces every writable segment, so llvmpipe cannot run there at all. The
  optional wxallow kernel patch (cc9/kernel/ in the agent9 repo) adds a gated,
  per-segment opt-in; `wxallow=1` in plan9.ini turns it on.

    - Patched kernel + wxallow=1 -> llvmpipe, automatically.
    - Stock kernel (the default)  -> softpipe, exactly as in 0.1.0. Nothing
                                     breaks; you just don't get the speedup.

  Check what you'd get:  gl9 driver
  Force a driver:        GALLIUM_DRIVER=softpipe gl9 cube

  SIZE: 6.9 MB -> ~40 MB. 9front has no dynamic linking, so each binary
  statically links all of LLVM. On a stock kernel that weight is dead — you
  download LLVM you cannot use. If that trades badly for you, stay on 0.1.0:
  it is unchanged and still correct.

  Also in this release:
    - The launcher only forces GALLIUM_NOSSE=1 on the softpipe path now (where
      it is still needed: softpipe's own x86 vertex-fetch JIT NX-faults on a
      stock kernel). On a wxallow kernel that JIT works and the flag is dropped.
    - New: `gl9 driver` prints which rasterizer would be used.

0.1.0
  First release. OpenGL 3.3 via Mesa softpipe (OSMesa), presented to a rio
  window by gl9win. Pixel-exact against host Mesa on the 6-test parity corpus.
  Demos: `gl9 cube` (lit spinning cube), `gl9 egl` (triangle through EGL).
